Sorry I was not writing down the juveniles as I was using the old data form in the field.  Most of the unbanded, unknown sex, birds looked to have the scaled juvenile feathers.  My number of 6 may be a little high for juveniles.

All of the birds this year were adjacent to the restoration area to the south, whereas in the past two years the birds were near the northern park boundary.  This may be due to the large tides washing up much of the beach in the north and creating a sharp cut bank rather than a smooth slope or extended beach and wrack line like usual.

I did not make it all the way to the south jetty this year as the tide was coming in and running up the beach pretty high.  I do not believe I would have missed many birds as the beach gets steeper and much narrower with a lot of large wood and high bank the further south you go.

At Sitka, From spit opening south to beach access 34A, dune is now a 6-10 foot sand wall. Estuary mouth is moving south, all dunes at spit opening are now gone and only a small portion of one remains. No signage was seen in area. I counted 4 cars driving erratically around in the SPMA. Did not find any plovers at sitka, only found one track. 

At Sandlake, all plovers were in 5 loose groups, either foraging or roosting. Conditions were partly sunny, 58, and no wind. Significant acreage of suitable habitat has been added to the southern end of the fishermen's day use/ pedestrian only beach area. A lot of seaweed and detritus on sand. Conditions seem good for breeding habitat, flat, out of high tide zone, with a free-flowing structure. I encountered 5 people in area. In summer visitor use is much heavier.

column18:
Survey was split with Eleanor Gaines. Eleanor did the North end of the spit, while I did the south end.

1. Suspected Plover tracks observed (45.510672, -123.956483). Eleanor Gaines suspects they are plover tracks. Dave Lauten can't tell and says they could be plover or Western/Least Sanderling. two photos were taken of the tracks.

2. Bald eagle (HALE) observed flying overhead (45.526926, -123.953321)

General: Lots of families and dogs at the beach and the tide was on it's way out. Observed possible plover tracks along the way, but no birds were seen. It seems like the North end of the spit could have better plover habitat since there are less people up there.
Birds that frequent this area were reported north of the jetty this year
Entered by CStrong, 2.1.2021
Very little open dry sand; not great habitat. Take care with timing - steep sandy cliffs can trap surveyor when tide coming in, as beach is quite narrow for most of distance.
No plovers seen, though we saw some tracks - not particularly fresh.
No WSP observed. Low recreation and predators compared to prior years, one vehicle, three sea gulls. Conspecifics included one Clark’s grebe and approximately 100 dunlins.

We started at Lat: 42.54601  Lon: -124.39668 and walked North until Lat: 42.56123  Lon: -124.39177 which is about 0.08 miles.  Then drove to Ophir rest area to start at Lat: 42.53624  Lon: -124.40074 and walked North until we reached the first spot we started. We had the sun to our backs when walking North. It was sunny and 5 to 10 mile/hr wind. There were 4 people, 2 dogs, and 2 common ravens during the survey on the beach at the Ophir rest area.
No sign of snowy plover. However potential predator tracks in the sand were present, such as raccoons, dogs, and possibly bobcat.

No birds observed, but found fresh snowy plover tracks near north jetty--high on wide section of beach above large amount of intertidal large wood debris. High visitor traffic: ~160 pedestrian, 21 dog. Weather: clear, 60+ F, <5 mph NNE
Habitat was much changed due to recent winter storms.  Huge amount of logs on beach and river had breached in several locations.

Little habitat - I've said this before, but I think this route could be eliminated.  The beach is narrow and backed by grass-covered bluffs.  There is little area available for plovers to forage much less nest.  Also the Elk River is moving north, so the route is becoming shorter.

column18: Siltcoos Breach to Siuslaw South Jetty, no plovers were sighted

Recent storm activity left degraded habitat conditions; wind and wave action on the beach left little debris in the wrack line. No plovers observed. Crows (n=7), ravens (n=2) and off-leash dogs (n=12) plus lots of people. Also tire tracks observed through almost all of the route despite it being south of the drive-in access. All of these problems persist year after year but all seem worse this year. Shorebird breeding site sign is not up at the trailhead again just like last year - likely state agency budget impact. Spoke with a very knowledgeable local birder who has seen plover activity on the beach south of the spit, north of Seaside and closer to the river mouth, but not confirmed nesting. Gave him my card and asked him to contact me if he does confirm nesting.

This site was split with E. Gaines. Results of this survey are for the southern portion of the spit. Below are observations made during the survey.
- Tracks from mopeds along the wrack line (see photo)
- Helicopter flying over back and forth at the beginning of the survey (they were pretty close too)
- 9 whimbrel observed foraging along the shoreline at the start of the survey
- 4 crows flying over dunes and landing within survey area
- 35 whimbrel foraging along foredunes throughout the survey
- 9 semi-palmated plovers observed foraging along the shoreline during the survey
- 1 Dunlin observed foraging along the shorline
- 60+ whimbrel observed foraging along shoreline during the survey
- 24 western sandpiper observed foraging along the shoreline during the survey

The Elk River's mouth changed location, enabling me to walk from the Cape Blanco survey area all the way to the end of the Elk River survey area (used to have to drive around the river and do the two surveys separately).  I suspect it will change back shortly.  This was convenient, but also meant that driving was easier too (the beach is open to driving) and there were many, many vehicle tracks all through the habitat, and garbage was burned too.  Planning on going back with landowner to collect garbage.  No shorebirds of any kind.  Native plant community is doing awesome! YSB all over the place, morning glory, beach pea.  Over-washing plus river moving took out a lot of beach grass.  Beautiful day and interesting changes, but a bummer about all the tracks.  If there was a nest there it would have gotten run over.

column18: Very difficult reading bands with many people (40+) and off leash dogs pushing (15+) birds around. Plovers were hanging in a couple separate groups and would get flushed and settle to roost along the wrack line in footprints where their legs weren't visible. We were able to count 37 birds on the ground at one time but with the constant flushing it was difficult to truly tally by sex and read the bands. A large nervous flock of dunlin and sanderlings also helped keep the plovers moving.  All of the plovers were in the area roughly adjacent to the southern most campground beach entrance.  I believe out from the 22b sign.

No plovers seen during the winter survey. Sandpipers and Sanderlings were the most common bird species seen on the Camp Rilea transect.

The river mouth is coming out at starting point.  Able to walk out onto the spit from private ranch (with landowner) and go north but not south.  Able to walk all the way to Cape Blanco access.  No shorebirds of any kind.

Overcast with heavy mist, ~40 F, wind S 5-10 mph, near low tide. Few shorebird tracks at approx. middle of site, possible SNPL. 10 pedestrian, 3 dogs. SAND x1, gull spp x60, CORA x1. Dead calf carcass at north end. Middle of site is relatively wide, approx. 150m near State Parks parking lot.

When first arriving on the beach, we noticed one individual being pursued by a peregrine falcon. H.Renn feels confident pursuant was SNPL, but unable to confirm. When finishing survey and exiting to parking lot (Fisherman's Day Use), peregrine was observed perched with white down feather stuck to talons. Potential predation of aforementioned peep? Large group of sanderlings near OHV area and tracks that appeared to be SNPL close to "Pedestrian Only" signage. No other observations.

Some tracks observed along linear  portion of beach. No observations of birds likely due to disturbance from machinery working on dunes. High concentration of dog tracks (multiple dogs, large breed and medium) in spit area; might be possible that workers are bringing pets to construction site?
